{"title_page": "Adam Smith (coach)", "text_new": "{{Other people|Adam Smith}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Adam Smith\n| image = Adam Charles Smith.png\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1971|10|27|df=y}}<ref>{{soccerway|adam-smith/538572}}</ref>\n| birth_place = England\n| position = [[Goalkeeper]]\n| currentclub = \n| youthyears1 = 1988\n| youthclubs1 = [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]\n| youthyears2 = 1989\n| youthclubs2 = [[Chatteris Town]]\n| youthyears3 = 1989\n| youthclubs3 = [[Cambridge United]]\n| youthyears4 = 1990\n| youthclubs4 = [[Winsford United]]\n| years1 = 1992\n| clubs1 = [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]]\n| years2 = 1992\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Holywell Town F.C.|Holywell Town]] (loan)\n| years3 = 1992\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[Mold Alexandra]] (loan)\n| years4 = 1994\n| clubs4 = [[Los Angeles Salsa]]\n| years5 = 1997\n| clubs5 = [[Soham Town Rangers]]\n| years6 = 1998\n| clubs6 = [[Harrogate Town]]\n| years7 = 1999\n| clubs7 = [[Geylang United]]\n| years8 = 1999\n| clubs8 = [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]]\n| years9 = 1999\u20132001\n| clubs9 = [[Long Island Rough Riders]]\n| years10 = 2002\u20132004\n| clubs10 = [[Wilmington Hammerheads]]\n| manageryears1 = 2010\u20132012\n| managerclubs1 = [[Portland Timbers]] (GK Coach/Reserve Head Assistant)\n| manageryears2 = 2014\u20132017\n| managerclubs2 = [[Sacramento Republic]] (Head Assistant)\n| youthyears5 = 1991\n| youthclubs5 = [[Crewe Alexandra]]\n| managerclubs3 = [[Fresno FC]] (Head Coach/Manager)\n| manageryears3 = 2017-2019\n}}\n\n'''Adam Smith''' is an English (now US citizen) football coach and former goalkeeper who was most recently head coach of [[USL Championship]] side [[Fresno FC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fresnofc.com/news_article/show/854231?referrer_id=3067476|title=Fresno FC Announces Adam Smith As First-Ever Head Coach|publisher=Fresno Football Club|date=November 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fresnobee.com/sports/soccer/article183677776.html|title=Fresno FC takes another step toward 2018 debut. New coach will meet public Monday|publisher=Fresno Bee|date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> Smith took the team to 3rd place in the [[USL Championship]] Western Conference in only its 2nd season in the league. This was Smith\u2019s first Head Managerial position of a Senior Team (aside from two interim games with Sacramento Republic). Unfortunately, after the successful first two years, the Fresno FC ownership group decided to cease operations at the end of the 2019 season. This was for non-soccer related matters and was in part due to not being able to secure a soccer specific stadium.\n\nPrior to his time at Fresno, Smith was formerly the Assistant Head Coach at [[Sacramento Republic FC|Sacramento Republic]] helping the club achieve a 1st place Western Conference finish in 2016.  During his tenure at Sacramento Republic, he also served as the Technical Director at Elk Grove Youth Soccer Club.\n\nSmith's professional coaching career started as a player/assistant coach at [[Wilmington Hammerheads FC|Wilmington Hammerheads]] in the [[USL Second Division|USL D-3 Pro League]] in 2001. Later in his career he joined [[Portland Timbers]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timbers.com/post/2010/04/14/timbers-name-adam-smith-clubs-goalkeeper-coach-0|title=Timbers name Adam Smith as club's goalkeeper coach|date=April 14, 2010|work=Portland Timbers|access-date=November 12, 2017|language=en}}</ref> where he became the inaugural Goalkeeping Coach for the teams' first year in Major League Soccer. Smith later went on to be the club's first Academy Director,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timbers.com/post/2011/12/13/timbers-name-adam-smith-academy-and-youth-goalkeeping-director|title=Timbers name Adam Smith an Academy and Youth Goalkeeping Director|date=December 13, 2011|work=Portland Timbers|access-date=November 12, 2017|language=en}}</ref> along with co-director Mike Smith. After serving 5 years with the MLS club he moved to return to first team professional football with Sacramento at the start of the 2015 season, to work alongside then head coach [[Preki|Predrag Radosavljevi\u0107]] (Preki). Prior to starting his professional coaching career, Smith previously played professional soccer as a goalkeeper in the US with [[Long Island Rough Riders]] and Wilmington Hammerheads. Smith also gained professional playing experience in England, Scotland, Wales and South East Asia before moving permanently to the United States. He is the son of [[Graham Smith (footballer, born 1947)|Graham Smith]], an ex-professional English footballer who was previously a director at [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] of the [[Premier League|English Premier League]].\n\n==Career==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=December 2017}}\n\n'''Playing career'''\nSmith, who played as goalkeeper, began his professional playing career in 1992 after graduating from [[Manchester Metropolitan University]] in England with a degree in business and sports coaching. Smith also represented England Independent Schoolboys at both the U16 and U19 levels. Additionally he represented a British Colleges X1 in 1992.  Smith did not make a British league full appearance but was able to ply his trade in non-league football (making over 200 first team semi-professional appearances). He then went on work in the US as a full-time professional, playing in the second division league before moving into full-time coaching.\n\n'''Coaching career'''\n\nSmith (originally from England and now a US citizen) has over thirty years of domestic and international experience as a coach and player.\n\n==Personal life==\nSmith lives in California with his wife and two children. Smith also qualified as a financial advisor. During his part-time professional playing, he worked for an insurance company and a national banking institution. His father, [[Graham Smith (footballer, born 1947)|Graham Smith]], was a professional footballer. Graham Smith has had over 200 English league appearances as a professional player and has helped to build Sacramento Republic to a Championship winning team as the clubs first ever Director of Football.\n\n==Honors==\n; Playing\n\n* USL National Championship winner, Long island Rough Riders, 2002\n* USL National Championship winner, Wilmington Hammerheads, 2003\n\n; Coaching\n\n* USL PDL National Championship winner, Portland Timbers u23s, 2010\n* USL playoffs 2nd place Western conference, Portland Timbers, 2010\n* MLS Goalkeeper player of the year (Troy Perkins), Portland Timbers, 2011\n* MLS Reserve Team 2nd-place position, Portland Timbers, 2011\n* USL Western conference playoffs, Sacramento Republic, 2015\n* USL 1st place Western conference, Sacramento Republic, 2016\n* US Open Cup round of 16, Sacramento Republic, 2017\n* USL Western conference semi-finals, Sacramento Republic, 2017\n\n==Coaching qualifications==\nUefa A license (Welsh Football Association)\n\nEnglish Preliminary Award (English FA)\n\nUSSF A license (US Soccer)\n\nUSSF National GK license (US Soccer)\n\nUSSF Pro B license (US Soccer)\n\nNSCAA National GK License (Utd Soccer coaches)\n\nNSCAA Director of Coaching (Utd Soccer coaches)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Adam}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sports in Fresno, California]]\n[[Category:Fresno FC coaches]]\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:English football managers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|Adam Smith}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Adam Smith\n| image = Adam Charles Smith.png\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1971|10|27|df=y}}<ref>{{soccerway|adam-smith/538572}}</ref>\n| birth_place = England\n| position = [[Goalkeeper]]\n| currentclub = \n| youthyears1 = 1988\n| youthclubs1 = [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]\n| youthyears2 = 1989\n| youthclubs2 = [[Chatteris Town]]\n| youthyears3 = 1989\n| youthclubs3 = [[Cambridge United]]\n| youthyears4 = 1990\n| youthclubs4 = [[Winsford United]]\n| years1 = 1992\n| clubs1 = [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]]\n| years2 = 1992\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Holywell Town F.C.|Holywell Town]] (loan)\n| years3 = 1992\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[Mold Alexandra]] (loan)\n| years4 = 1994\n| clubs4 = [[Los Angeles Salsa]]\n| years5 = 1997\n| clubs5 = [[Soham Town Rangers]]\n| years6 = 1998\n| clubs6 = [[Harrogate Town]]\n| years7 = 1999\n| clubs7 = [[Geylang United]]\n| years8 = 1999\n| clubs8 = [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]]\n| years9 = 1999\u20132001\n| clubs9 = [[Long Island Rough Riders]]\n| years10 = 2002\u20132004\n| clubs10 = [[Wilmington Hammerheads]]\n| manageryears1 = 2010\u20132012\n| managerclubs1 = [[Portland Timbers]] (GK Coach/Reserve Head Assistant)\n| manageryears2 = 2014\u20132017\n| managerclubs2 = [[Sacramento Republic]] (Head Assistant)\n| youthyears5 = 1991\n| youthclubs5 = [[Crewe Alexandra]]\n| managerclubs3 = [[Fresno FC]] (Head Coach/Manager)\n| manageryears3 = 2018-2019\n}}\n\n'''Adam Smith''' is an English (now US citizen) football coach and former goalkeeper who was most recently head coach of [[USL Championship]] side [[Fresno FC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fresnofc.com/news_article/show/854231?referrer_id=3067476|title=Fresno FC Announces Adam Smith As First-Ever Head Coach|publisher=Fresno Football Club|date=November 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fresnobee.com/sports/soccer/article183677776.html|title=Fresno FC takes another step toward 2018 debut. New coach will meet public Monday|publisher=Fresno Bee|date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> Smith took the team to 3rd place in the [[USL Championship]] Western Conference in only its 2nd season in the league. This was Smith\u2019s first Head Managerial position of a Senior Team (aside from two interim games with Sacramento Republic). Unfortunately, after the successful first two years, the Fresno FC ownership group decided to cease operations at the end of the 2019 season. This was for non-soccer related matters and was in part due to not being able to secure a soccer specific stadium.\n\nPrior to his time at Fresno, Smith was formerly the Assistant Head Coach at [[Sacramento Republic FC|Sacramento Republic]] helping the club achieve a 1st place Western Conference finish in 2016.  During his tenure at Sacramento Republic, he also served as the Technical Director at Elk Grove Youth Soccer Club.\n\nSmith's professional coaching career started as a player/assistant coach at [[Wilmington Hammerheads FC|Wilmington Hammerheads]] in the [[USL Second Division|USL D-3 Pro League]] in 2001. Later in his career he joined [[Portland Timbers]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timbers.com/post/2010/04/14/timbers-name-adam-smith-clubs-goalkeeper-coach-0|title=Timbers name Adam Smith as club's goalkeeper coach|date=April 14, 2010|work=Portland Timbers|access-date=November 12, 2017|language=en}}</ref> where he became the inaugural Goalkeeping Coach for the teams' first year in Major League Soccer. Smith later went on to be the club's first Academy Director,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timbers.com/post/2011/12/13/timbers-name-adam-smith-academy-and-youth-goalkeeping-director|title=Timbers name Adam Smith an Academy and Youth Goalkeeping Director|date=December 13, 2011|work=Portland Timbers|access-date=November 12, 2017|language=en}}</ref> along with co-director Mike Smith. After serving 5 years with the MLS club he moved to return to first team professional football with Sacramento at the start of the 2015 season, to work alongside then head coach [[Preki|Predrag Radosavljevi\u0107]] (Preki). Prior to starting his professional coaching career, Smith previously played professional soccer as a goalkeeper in the US with [[Long Island Rough Riders]] and Wilmington Hammerheads. Smith also gained professional playing experience in England, Scotland, Wales and South East Asia before moving permanently to the United States. He is the son of [[Graham Smith (footballer, born 1947)|Graham Smith]], an ex-professional English footballer who was previously a director at [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] of the [[Premier League|English Premier League]].\n\n==Career==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=December 2017}}\n\n'''Playing career'''\nSmith, who played as goalkeeper, began his professional playing career in 1992 after graduating from [[Manchester Metropolitan University]] in England with a degree in business and sports coaching. Smith also represented England Independent Schoolboys at both the U16 and U19 levels. Additionally he represented a British Colleges X1 in 1992.  Smith did not make a British league full appearance but was able to ply his trade in non-league football (making over 200 first team semi-professional appearances). He then went on work in the US as a full-time professional, playing in the second division league before moving into full-time coaching.\n\n'''Coaching career'''\n\nSmith (originally from England and now a US citizen) has over thirty years of domestic and international experience as a coach and player.\n\n==Personal life==\nSmith lives in California with his wife and two children. Smith also qualified as a financial advisor. During his part-time professional playing, he worked for an insurance company and a national banking institution. His father, [[Graham Smith (footballer, born 1947)|Graham Smith]], was a professional footballer. Graham Smith has had over 200 English league appearances as a professional player and has helped to build Sacramento Republic to a Championship winning team as the clubs first ever Director of Football.\n\n==Honors==\n; Playing\n\n* USL National Championship winner, Long island Rough Riders, 2002\n* USL National Championship winner, Wilmington Hammerheads, 2003\n\n; Coaching\n\n* USL PDL National Championship winner, Portland Timbers u23s, 2010\n* USL playoffs 2nd place Western conference, Portland Timbers, 2010\n* MLS Goalkeeper player of the year (Troy Perkins), Portland Timbers, 2011\n* MLS Reserve Team 2nd-place position, Portland Timbers, 2011\n* USL Western conference playoffs, Sacramento Republic, 2015\n* USL 1st place Western conference, Sacramento Republic, 2016\n* US Open Cup round of 16, Sacramento Republic, 2017\n* USL Western conference semi-finals, Sacramento Republic, 2017\n\n==Coaching qualifications==\nUefa A license (Welsh Football Association)\n\nEnglish Preliminary Award (English FA)\n\nUSSF A license (US Soccer)\n\nUSSF National GK license (US Soccer)\n\nUSSF Pro B license (US Soccer)\n\nNSCAA National GK License (Utd Soccer coaches)\n\nNSCAA Director of Coaching (Utd Soccer coaches)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Adam}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sports in Fresno, California]]\n[[Category:Fresno FC coaches]]\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:English football managers]]\n", "name_user": "Richardpatrick11", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adam_Smith_(coach)"}
{"title_page": "Elizabeth Losey", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{short description|American biologist and environmentalist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Elizabeth Losey\n| image         = Betty Losey (Seney National Wildlife Refuge).jpg\n| alt           =\n| caption       = {{small|Betty Losey doing field work at Seney National Wildlife Refuge.}}\n| birth_name    = Elizabeth Brown Beard\n| birth_date       = {{Birth year|1912}}\n| birth_place      =\n| death_date       = {{Death year and age|2005|1912}}\n| death_place   =\n| nationality   = American\n| alma_mater    = University of Michigan\n| other_names   =\n| occupation    = [[Conservation (ethic)|Conservation]]<br>Refuge biology\n| years_active  =\n| known_for     =\n| notable_works =\n| spouse        =\n}}\n'''Elizabeth Brown Losey''' (n\u00e9e '''Beard''') was an American conservationist who is recognised as being the first female [[Wildlife refuge|refuge]] biologist.\n\n== Education ==\nLosey was born in [[East Orange, New Jersey]] in 1912.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.conservationgateway.org/ConservationByGeography/NorthAmerica/UnitedStates/michigan/projects/Documents/Landscape%20Stewardship%20Stories/32.FirstFemaleFieldBiologist.pdf|title=The First Female Field Biologist|website=Conservation Gateway|access-date=March 12, 2018}}</ref> She went to high school in [[Lynn, Massachusetts]].<ref name=\":0\" /> She graduated from the [[University of Michigan]] with a degree in [[wildlife management]] and conservation in 1946.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fws.gov/refuges/about/conservationheroes/ElizabethBettyLosey_07202012.html|title=A Look Back: Elizabeth \"Betty\" Losey {{!}} National Wildlife Refuge System|last=System|first=National Wildlife Refuge|website=www.fws.gov|language=en|access-date=March 12, 2018}}</ref> Initially, Losey could not find work because she was a woman.<ref name=\":1\" /> She worked as a research assistant for the [[University of Michigan]] until 1952.<ref name=\":0\" /> She created a series of teaching aids in wildlife management, including the ''Outline of upland game bird management'' (1947).<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/001508918|title=Outline of upland game bird management|last=University of Michigan.|last2=Beard|first2=Elizabeth Sherwood Browne.|date=1951|publisher=Overbeck Co.|location=Ann Arbor}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nIn 1947 she was employed by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Commission as a biologist at [[Seney National Wildlife Refuge]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nmu.edu/sites/DrupalArchives/files/UserFiles//MSS-004.html|title=Elizabeth Browne Beard Losey papers|website=www.nmu.edu|access-date=March 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223162117/http://www.nmu.edu/sites/DrupalArchives/files/UserFiles/MSS-004.html|archive-date=February 23, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Her assignment was to understand the importance of beavers in waterfowl management.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://training.fws.gov/History/ConservationHeroes/Losey.html|title=USFWS/NCTC - History and Heritage|last=Webmaster|first=NCTC|website=training.fws.gov|access-date=March 12, 2018}}</ref> Losey was the first woman research biologist in the country.<ref name=\":0\" /> She quit when she was told she was being transferred West, as by that time \"romance had crept in\".<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://northerntradition.wordpress.com/2014/05/22/collection-spotlight-the-elizabeth-brown-beard-losey-papers/|title=Collection Spotlight: The Elizabeth Brown Beard Losey Papers|date=May 22, 2014|work=The Northern Tradition|access-date=March 12, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> She was only employed by the agency for three years, but built up a successful career as an [[ornithologist]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.webpages.uidaho.edu/WINR/klinger.htm|title=klinger.htm|website=www.webpages.uidaho.edu|access-date=March 12, 2018}}</ref> [[Rachel Carson]] recognised Losey's preparations for a manuscript on [[trumpeter swan]]<nowiki/>s as \"an excellent job of organizing the material for an effective story\".<ref name=\":4\" /> In 1964 she published her observation of duck broods at the Seney National Wildlife Refuge.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Beard|first=Elizabeth B.|date=1964|title=Duck Brood Behavior at the Seney National Wildlife Refuge|jstor=3798202|journal=The Journal of Wildlife Management|volume=28|issue=3|pages=492\u2013521|doi=10.2307/3798202}}</ref>\n\nLosey travelled America and Canada taking photographs of fur trading posts and collecting Native American art, which was later donated to the DeVos Art Museum in [[Michigan]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/devosartmuseum/sets/72157607791240700/|title=Losey Collection of Native American Art and Artifact|work=Flickr|access-date=March 12, 2018|language=en-us}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /> Losey wrote two books. ''Let Them Be Remembered: The Story of the Fur Trade Forts'', the story of the [[Hudson's Bay Company]] and the 1600 fur trade, was published in 1999.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/44722618|title=Let them be remembered : the story of the fur trade forts|last=Browne.|first=Losey, Elizabeth|date=1999|publisher=Vantage Press|isbn=0533125723|edition= 1st|location=New York|oclc=44722618}}</ref> Her second, ''Seney National Wildlife Refuge: its story'', was published in 2003.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/54206811|title=Seney National Wildlife Refuge : its story|last=Browne.|first=Losey, Elizabeth|date=2003|publisher=E.B. Losey|isbn=0972783407|edition= 1st|location=[United States?]|oclc=54206811}}</ref> She remained a volunteer at [[Seney National Wildlife Refuge]] until her death in 2005.<ref name=\":1\" /> She wrote her final peer-reviewed paper at the age of 92 on the History of the [[Sharp-tailed grouse|Sharp-tailed Grouse]], which was published after her death.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fws.gov/uploadedFiles/Losey2007.pdf|title=History of Sharp-tailed Grouse (Tympanuchus phasianellus) at Seney National Wildlife Refuge and Surrounding Areas, Schoolcraft County, Michigan|last=Losey|first=Elizabeth|website=U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service Home Page|access-date=March 12, 2018}}</ref> She was a lifetime sponsor of [[Delta Waterfowl Foundation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deltawaterfowl.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/DW_AnnualReport_2016.pdf|title=2016 Annual Report|website=Delta Waterfowl|access-date=March 12, 2018}}</ref> She is regarded as a pioneer in gender equality within fieldwork.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Losey, Elizabeth}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:2005 deaths]]\n[[Category:Women conservationists]]\n[[Category:American conservationists]]\n[[Category:American women biologists]]\n[[Category:People from East Orange, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Scientists from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{short description|American biologist and environmentalist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Elizabeth Losey\n| image         = Betty Losey (Seney National Wildlife Refuge).jpg\n| alt           =\n| caption       = {{small|Betty Losey doing field work at Seney National Wildlife Refuge.}}\n| birth_name    = Elizabeth Brown Beard\n| birth_date       = {{Birth year|1912}}\n| birth_place      =\n| death_date       = {{Death year and age|2005|1912}}\n| death_place   =\n| nationality   = American\n| alma_mater    = University of Michigan\n| other_names   =\n| occupation    = [[Conservation (ethic)|Conservation]]<br>Refuge biology\n| years_active  =\n| known_for     =\n| notable_works =\n| spouse        =\n}}\n'''Elizabeth Brown Losey''' (n\u00e9e '''Beard''') was an American conservationist who is recognised as being the first female [[Wildlife refuge|refuge]] biologist.\n\n== Education ==\nLosey was born in [[East Orange, New Jersey]] in 1912.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.conservationgateway.org/ConservationByGeography/NorthAmerica/UnitedStates/michigan/projects/Documents/Landscape%20Stewardship%20Stories/32.FirstFemaleFieldBiologist.pdf|title=The First Female Field Biologist|website=Conservation Gateway|access-date=March 12, 2018}}</ref> She went to high school in [[Lynn, Massachusetts]].<ref name=\":0\" /> She graduated from the [[University of Michigan]] with a degree in [[wildlife management]] and conservation in 1946.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fws.gov/refuges/about/conservationheroes/ElizabethBettyLosey_07202012.html|title=A Look Back: Elizabeth \"Betty\" Losey {{!}} National Wildlife Refuge System|last=System|first=National Wildlife Refuge|website=www.fws.gov|language=en|access-date=March 12, 2018}}</ref> Initially, Losey could not find work because she was a woman.<ref name=\":1\" /> She worked as a research assistant for the [[University of Michigan]] until 1952.<ref name=\":0\" /> She created a series of teaching aids in wildlife management, including the ''Outline of upland game bird management'' (1947).<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/001508918|title=Outline of upland game bird management|last=University of Michigan.|last2=Beard|first2=Elizabeth Sherwood Browne.|date=1951|publisher=Overbeck Co.|location=Ann Arbor}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nIn 1947 she was employed by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Commission as a biologist at [[Seney National Wildlife Refuge]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nmu.edu/sites/DrupalArchives/files/UserFiles//MSS-004.html|title=Elizabeth Browne Beard Losey papers|website=www.nmu.edu|access-date=March 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223162117/http://www.nmu.edu/sites/DrupalArchives/files/UserFiles/MSS-004.html|archive-date=February 23, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Her assignment was to understand the importance of beavers in waterfowl management.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://training.fws.gov/History/ConservationHeroes/Losey.html|title=USFWS/NCTC - History and Heritage|last=Webmaster|first=NCTC|website=training.fws.gov|access-date=March 12, 2018}}</ref> Losey was the first woman research biologist in the country.<ref name=\":0\" /> She quit when she was told she was being transferred West, as by that time \"romance had crept in\".<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://northerntradition.wordpress.com/2014/05/22/collection-spotlight-the-elizabeth-brown-beard-losey-papers/|title=Collection Spotlight: The Elizabeth Brown Beard Losey Papers|date=May 22, 2014|work=The Northern Tradition|access-date=March 12, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> She was only employed by the agency for three years, but built up a successful career as an [[ornithologist]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.webpages.uidaho.edu/WINR/klinger.htm|title=klinger.htm|website=www.webpages.uidaho.edu|access-date=March 12, 2018}}</ref> [[Rachel Carson]] recognised Losey's preparations for a manuscript on [[trumpeter swan]]<nowiki/>s as \"an excellent job of organizing the material for an effective story\".<ref name=\":4\" /> In 1964 she published her observation of duck broods at the Seney National Wildlife Refuge.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Beard|first=Elizabeth B.|date=1964|title=Duck Brood Behavior at the Seney National Wildlife Refuge|jstor=3798202|journal=The Journal of Wildlife Management|volume=28|issue=3|pages=492\u2013521|doi=10.2307/3798202}}</ref>\n\nLosey travelled America and Canada taking photographs of fur trading posts and collecting Native American art, which was later donated to the DeVos Art Museum in [[Michigan]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/devosartmuseum/sets/72157607791240700/|title=Losey Collection of Native American Art and Artifact|work=Flickr|access-date=March 12, 2018|language=en-us}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /> Losey wrote two books. ''Let Them Be Remembered: The Story of the Fur Trade Forts'', the story of the [[Hudson's Bay Company]] and the 1600 fur trade, was published in 1999.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/44722618|title=Let them be remembered : the story of the fur trade forts|last=Browne.|first=Losey, Elizabeth|date=1999|publisher=Vantage Press|isbn=0533125723|edition= 1st|location=New York|oclc=44722618}}</ref> Her second, ''Seney National Wildlife Refuge: its story'', was published in 2003.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/54206811|title=Seney National Wildlife Refuge : its story|last=Browne.|first=Losey, Elizabeth|date=2003|publisher=E.B. Losey|isbn=0972783407|edition= 1st|location=[United States?]|oclc=54206811}}</ref> She remained a volunteer at [[Seney National Wildlife Refuge]] until her death in 2005.<ref name=\":1\" /> She wrote her final peer-reviewed paper at the age of 92 on the History of the [[Sharp-tailed grouse|Sharp-tailed Grouse]], which was published after her death.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fws.gov/uploadedFiles/Losey2007.pdf|title=History of Sharp-tailed Grouse (Tympanuchus phasianellus) at Seney National Wildlife Refuge and Surrounding Areas, Schoolcraft County, Michigan|last=Losey|first=Elizabeth|website=U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service Home Page|access-date=March 12, 2018}}</ref> She was a lifetime sponsor of [[Delta Waterfowl Foundation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deltawaterfowl.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/DW_AnnualReport_2016.pdf|title=2016 Annual Report|website=Delta Waterfowl|access-date=March 12, 2018}}</ref> She is regarded as a pioneer in gender equality within fieldwork.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Losey, Elizabeth}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:2005 deaths]]\n[[Category:Women conservationists]]\n[[Category:American conservationists]]\n[[Category:Women biologists]]\n[[Category:American women biologists]]\n[[Category:People from East Orange, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Scientists from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan 